AGI - The former head of French intelligence Bernard Squarcini>, 69 years old, was sentenced to four years in prison, two of which were suspended, and a fine of 200,000 euros for using his security contacts in order to obtain confidential information and privileges for the benefit, in particular, of the managing director of Lvmh Bernard Arnault>.
&nbsp;
Squarcini - nicknamed "the shark" - was tried for eleven crimes, ranging from the traffic of passive influences to the undue appropriation of public funds, including the impairment of national defence secrets, the falsification of public documents and complicity in the violation of professional secrecy.
<div </div
The tribunal yesterday acquitted him by some accusations > and reclassified others. In particular, the former head of French intelligence was held responsible for monitoring, between 2013 and 2016, journalist Francois Ruffin and his newspaper Fakir, on behalf of the French group. At the time, Francois Ruffin, today deputy of the ecologist group and possible presidential candidate in 2027, was filming the film 'Merci patron!' - rewarded with Cesar for the best documentary in 2017 - and he wanted to interview the French group's CEO who controls almost two thirds of the fashion market. Arnault, during his testimony at the hearing, has never been accused, has always denied being aware of a plan for his group, even accusing Ruffin to "strumentalize" the process. Immediately after the verdict, Ruffin argued that with this judgment it was established that "there was collusion between the French colossus - first in Europe by capitalization - and the former number one of the services of the country".&nbsp;
&nbsp;
According to the accusation, in 2008 Squarcini indebtedly commissioned agents of the Central Direction of Internal Intelligence (Dcri) to supervise "a man who (according to him) wanted to blackmail Bernard Arnault", obtained secret information from the police - also on the murder of lawyer Antoine Sollacaro, and took advantage of his knowledge to facilitate the procedures of passport and visa. The defence lawyers, who had asked for absolution, denounced a "singular lack of impartiality" in conducting investigations by the instructor judges, as well as a "default of contradiction", announcing that they will appeal.
&nbsp;
The Paris Criminal Court also banned Squarcini from exercising intelligence and counseling for five years, while the final part of his detention penalty will be granted under an electronic bracelet. The court also underlined that Squarcini used its powers and means of the State "to satisfy private interests", "designed and validated a system of close surveillance of the activity and members of an association whose existence was perfectly legal".
&nbsp;
In the course of the trial, the Prosecutor of the Republic had asked four years of imprisonment with the suspension of the conditional of the penalty and a fine of 300,000 euros for Squarcini, a "high emeritus official", guilty according to him of "extremely serious facts". Also several police officers and economic intelligence consultants were under trial along with Squarcini and seven of them were sentenced to penalties ranging from six months in prison with parole to three years in prison, two of which always with conditional suspension of the penalty, and a fine of 75,000 euros. Among the inquiries were the former court magistrate of Paris Laurent Marcadier and Prefect Pierre Lieutaud. Both were acquitted.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
